member.remarks:
This method does not use casting to make the target  value to be converted into a  value.
If the type  has implemented , C# language will allow this type
using -like operators  && and  ||
to determine multiple  values are  or  via the specified way
to be checked. This is just like C programming language rule - allowing any implicit casts from an integer to a boolean value like:

if (integer) // integer != 0 in C and op_True(integer) in C#
{
    // ...
}

The backing implementation is like the following code in C#:

struct Int32
{
    public static bool operator true(int value) => value != 0;
    public sttaic bool operator false(int value) => value == 0;
}

You can use this to create customized recursive lambda:

//                           T TResult
var factorial = YCombinator<int, int>(lambda => x => x == 0 ? 1 : x * lambda(x - 1));
//                          ~~~  ~~~
int result = factorial(5); // T -> TResult
Console.WriteLine(result);

This method allows you using  loop to iterate this value:

foreach (var bit in 17)
{
    // Do something...
}

For example:

byte value = 0b00010111;
foreach (int bitPos in value.SkipSetBit(2))
{
    yield return bitPos + 1;
}

You will get 3 and 5, because all set bit positions are 0, 1, 2 and 4, and we have skipped
two of them, so the result set bit positions to iterate on are only 2 and 4.

You can use this attribute to create a field:

[ImplicitField]
public int Property
{
    get => _property;
    set => _property ??= value;
}

You may not write code to create field _property. This attribute will make source generators generate it.

remarks.para:
The original way to declare a type with primary constructor is like:

public readonly struct Color(byte a, byte r, byte g, byte b)
{
    public byte A { get; } = a;
    public byte R { get; } = r;
    public byte G { get; } = g;
    public byte B { get; } = b;
}

Via this attribute type, we can simplify the code:

public readonly partial struct Color(
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte a,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte r,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte g,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte b
);

Such code is equivalent to the original one.

The original way to declare a type with primary constructor is like:

public readonly struct Color(byte a, byte r, byte g, byte b)
{
    public byte A { get; } = a;
    public byte R { get; } = r;
    public byte G { get; } = g;
    public byte B { get; } = b;
}

Via this attribute type, we can simplify the code:

public readonly partial struct Color(
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte a,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte r,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte g,
    [PrimaryConstructorParameter] byte b
);

Such code is equivalent to the original one.

Also, you can set the first character as lower or upper case via symbols < and >. If this property is "_<@", the generated member will be like:
private int _parameter = parameter;
where "<@" means the generated member name will use lower case for its first character.
